sec.p:
Floral scents are an important characteristic conferred by volatile compounds that play several key roles in flowering plants, primarily functioning to attract pollinators, particularly via long-distance communication (

; 

). Floral scents also play a significant role in plant defense against biotic and abiotic stresses by exerting toxic or deterrent activity against herbivores and microbes, repelling pests, minimizing damage caused by oxidative stress and ameliorating the effects of high temperatures (

; 

; 

). Floral fragrance is imperative critical characteristic that improves the aesthetic value of ornamental plants (

; 

). In addition, floral scent shows an important communication channel between plants and animals (

).

Floral fragrance is determined by a diverse mixture of low-molecular-weight compounds exhibiting high vapor pressures and low boiling points at ambient temperatures (

). Floral volatile compounds belong to 3 major groups: terpenoids, benzenoids/ phenylpropanoid, and derivatives of fatty acids. Among these major groups, the terpenoids are the largest class of floral volatiles, are structurally diverse and are the most abundant group of specialized plant metabolites (

). Terpenoids originate from two interconvertible five-carbon compounds, isopentenyl pyrophosphate (IPP) and dimethylallyl pyrophosphate (DMAPP), which are derived from two alternative but compartmentally separated pathways. In the cytosol, peroxisomes and endoplasmic reticulum, IPP is derived from acetyl-CoA through mevalonic acid (MVA) pathways, whereas in the plastids, it is synthesized from pyruvate and glyceraldehyde-3- phosphate (G3P) by methylerythritol phosphate (MEP) pathways (

; 

; 

). Although, subcellular compartmentation permits these pathways to act separately, metabolic ‘crosstalk’ has been revealed between them (

), especially from plastids to the cytosol (

; 

). The consecutive head-to-tail condensation of IPP and DMAPP by prenyltransferases produces the direct precursors of terpenes: geranyl diphosphate (GPP), geranylgeranyl diphosphate (GGPP) in plastids, and farnesyl diphosphate (FPP) in the cytosol. Thereafter, terpene synthase (TPS) converts GPP, FPP, and GGPP into cyclic and acyclic monoterpenes (
C
10
), sesquiterpenes (
C
15
) and diterpenes (
C
20
), respectively. Terpene synthases (TPSs) are the key enzymes involved in the biosynthetic pathways of terpenoids (

; 

; 

). TPS genes have been isolated and characterized from a variety of plants to study floral scent formation in ornamental plants.

The full-length open reading frames (ORF) of two terpene synthase genes designated LoTPS2 and LoTPS4 were identified from lily transcriptome unigenes (unpublished data) and amplified through PCR from the
Lilium
‘Siberia’ cDNA. LoTPS2 exhibits a putative ORF of 2265 bp and encodes a protein of 754 aa with a molecular mass of 87.7 kDa. Similarly, LoTPS4 exhibits a putative ORF of 1749 bp encoding a protein of 583 aa with a calculated molecular mass of 68.7 kDa. Plant terpene synthases are grouped into seven different subfamilies/clades, designated TPS-a through TPS-g, based on the relatedness of their amino acid sequences (
). Phylogenetic analysis revealed that LoTPS2 belongs to the TPS-f group ( Fig. 1a ). All TPS-f clade proteins, including LoTPS2 isolated in this study, contain 221 aa corresponding to the conifer diterpene internal sequence (CDIS) domain (
;
) ( Fig. 1b ). The highly conserved aspartate-rich motifs DDxxD and NSE/DTE which chelate divalent metal ions (especially Mg 2+ ) are also present in the Cterminal domains of both LoTPS2 and LoTPS4. Furthermore, LoTPS4 belongs to the TPS-b subfamily, which mainly contains angiosperm monoterpene synthases. The arginine-tryptophan rich motif RRX 8 W is found at the N-terminus of LoTPS4 but is absent in LoTPS2 ( Fig. 1c ). LoTPS4 also contains conserved RxR motifs upstream of DDxxD, which are modified to RxK motifs in LoTPS2. These motifs may take part in the initiation of the isomerization-cyclization reaction (
). The accession numbers of the genes are given in Supplementary Table 1.

LoTPS4 generated D-limonene (46.82%) and β- myrcene (31.65%) as its major products and β- phellandrene (10.22%), (+)-4-carene (9.07%) and 3-carene (2.24%) as its minor products when it was incubated in the presence of GPP (
Fig. 3
). Furthermore, recombinant LoTPS4 synthesized four sesquiterpenes, trans-α- bergamotene (56.84%), di-epi-α- cedrene (2.68%), α- cubebene (19.67%), and (
E
)-β- farnesene (20.81%) from FPP 
in vitro
(
Fig. 4b
). However, LoTPS4 did not produce any compounds when GGPP was used as a substrate (
Fig. 4a
).

According to phylogenetic analysis, LoTPS2 was grouped in the TPSf clade/subfamily of terpene synthases, which includes 

Clarkia breweri

mono-TPSs (

), 
Actinidia deliciosa
farnesene synthase 1 (

), 

Vitis vinifera
TPS (
Martin et al., 2010
)

, 

Malus domestica
TPS

30 (

) and 

Arabidopsis thaliana
TPS

04 (

). Interestingly, although LoTPS2 is not a di-TPS, it contains a conserved conifer diterpene internal sequence (CDIS) domain near the N-terminal region, which is a unique property of TPS-f clade members and di-TPSs (
Fig. 1
). It is assumed that this structural constituent existed in a general di-TPS ancestor and was lost during the evolution of mono-TPSs and sesqui-TPSs (

; 

). In addition, DDxxD and NSE/DTE motifs present at the C-terminus are responsible for the synchronization of divalent metal ions and substrate binding (

). In contrast, LoTPS4 belongs to the TPS-b clade, which includes the majority of mono-TPSs, mostly consisting of angiosperm mono-TPSs (

). The TPS-b subfamily frequently includes RRX 
8
W motifs, for the cyclization of mono-TPSs and plastid domains located in the N-terminal region of TPSs (

). The phylogenetic tree indicates that LoTPS2 and LoTPS4 might have exhibited diverse functions in floral scent formation during evolution.

Analysis of LoTPS2 and LoTPS4 expression levels in different organs and tissues of
Lilium
‘Siberia’ indicated that LoTPS2 was expressed in all plant parts, showing the highest levels in the petals followed by the sepals of the flower, which are the major sources of floral scent emissions ( Fig. 5 ). In contrast to LoTPS2 , LoTPS4 was most highly expressed in the filament of the flower, followed by the sepals and anthers of the flower. Our findings are consistent with a previous study showing that sepals and petals are the main sources of flower scent emissions (
;
;
). In
Lilium
‘Siberia’, LoTPS1 and LoTPS3 are highly expressed in the sepals and petals of the flower (
). In kiwifruit, two terpene synthases are responsible for the production of sesquiterpenes and are released mainly from the floral components of the plant (
). Similarly, in
Syringa oblata
and
S. oblata var. alba , SoLIM
is responsible for the production of limonene and is specifically expressed in the floral components of the plant (
). During flower developmental stages, the mRNA accumulation of LoTPS2 was very low at the flower bud stage and peaked at the full-bloom stage, then decreased at the senescence stage ( Fig. 6 ). Thus, the expression of LoTPS2 is developmentally-regulated and correlates with the floral scent emission pattern. In
Lilium
‘Siberia’, the emission of monoterpenes and the expression of LoTPS1 and LoTPS3 gradually increase with the development of flowers (
). LoTPS4 showed the highest expression beginning in the bud stage, while the D-limonene began to be released at the full-bloom stage. A similar pattern is observed in
S. oblata var. alba
, in which SoLIM shows its highest expression at the bud stage (
).

In 

Lilium

‘Siberia’, floral scent emissions exhibit rhythmic day/night rhythmic patterns. Under natural light conditions (12 h light/12 h dark), the expression pattern of 
LoTPS2
exhibits a diurnal circadian rhythm, with peak expression observed in the morning, followed by the afternoon and deep night (
Fig. 8a
). Likewise, the emission pattern of α-farnesene follows a diurnal circadian rhythm, peaking in the morning (
Fig. 8b
). However, 
LoTPS4
expression did not follow any circadian pattern (
Fig. 7b
). Nevertheless, the emission of D-limonene showed weak circadian oscillation (
Fig. 8d
). Our results are consistent with previous research showing that floral scent emissions in 

Lilium

‘Siberia’ exhibit diurnal circadian oscillations (

, 

). The expression of TPS genes and the emission of monoterpenes are positively correlated with each other (

). In 

Phalaenopsis bellina

and 

P. violacea

flowers, the emission of monoterpenes occurs during the daytime and their emission is mainly affected by the circadian clock (

). Most plants release the maximum amount of terpenoids in the daytime, regulated by an internal circadian clock or light (

). The emission of volatile organic compounds is highly regulated, and most of species are entertained to emit their scent compounds at a particular time during the day (

).

Moreover, the 
LoTPS2
gene responds to wounding injury of a flower (
Fig. 9
). Terpenoids play roles in signaling to other plants, defense against herbivores, insect repellences, and pollinator attraction and are the primary contributors to the chemical arsenal of plants (

; 

). In 

Populus trichocarpa
, 
PtTPS

2
is responsible for the biosynthesis of (
E
, 
E
)-α- farnesene and increases transcript abundance upon herbivory attack (

). Furthermore, the accumulation of 
HcFPPS
mRNA in 

H. coronarium

is induced by herbivory and mechanical injury (

). Similarly, an increase in the emission of farnesene and bergamotene is observed in maize upon herbivory attack (

).

Terpenoids are a structurally diverse group of specialized plant metabolites that play numerous ecophysiological roles in plant life. Here, two monoterpene synthases (
LoTPS2
and 
LoTPS4
) were cloned and functionally characterized. LoTPS2 is a sesquiterpene synthase that is responsible for the biosynthesis of (
E
, 
E
)-α- farnesene from FPP, whereas it produced no product when incubated with GPP or GGPP (
Fig. 2
). Previous studies have shown that (
E
, 
E
)-α- farnesene is involved in the conditioning and attraction of honeybees and other insects (

; 

). α- Farnesene also contributes to the scent properties of some fruits including melons (

) and apples (

). (
E
, 
E
)-α- farnesene plays a defensive role and acts as an attractant upon herbivory attack (

). Similarly, 
AFS1
cloned from the peel tissue of 

Malus domestica

fruit was shown to be responsible for the formation of (
E
, 
E
)-α- farnesene exclusively from FPP and to be involved in the production of ethylene (

).

In contrast to LoTPS2, LoTPS4 is a multiproduct enzyme that utilizes both GPP and FPP to produce monoterpenes and sesquiterpenes, respectively. LoTPS4 produces multiple monoterpenes (predominantly Dlimonene) from GPP and multiple sesquiterpenes (predominantly transα- bergamotene) from FPP. Numerous terpene synthases have been found that are capable of producing several terpenes from a single substrate (

; 

; 

; 

), and the profile of terpenes mostly includes one or two compounds that dominate as main products with others as minor products. Similarly, 
LaLIMS
from 

Lavandula angustifolia

flowers produces a blend of numerous monoterpenes, with limonene as a major product and terpinolene, pinene, camphene, α- phellandrene, and β- myrcene as minor products generated from GPP (

). Similarly, 
LaBERS
from 

Lavandula angustifolia

produces trans-α- bergamotene as a major product, while (
E
)-nerolidol, (
Z
)-α- bisabolene, (
E
)-β- farnesene and β- phellandrene are produced in smaller amounts from FPP. 
Cl
(+) 
LIMS1
and 
Cl
(+) 
LIMS2
from 

Citrus limon

generates almost exclusively limonene, with a lesser amount of α- pinene and β- myrcene from GPP (

). Limonene has many biochemical effects and is also recognized as an anticancer agent. Limonene has also been considered to be a safer food additive as compared to synthetic (

; 

). To our knowledge, this is the first report of limonene synthase from 

Lilium

‘Siberia’. Limonene possesses anti-carcinogenic properties and is widely used in the cosmetic and beverage industries (

; 

). The introduction of limonene synthase genes from 

C. breweri

into petunia resulted in linalool synthase production which repels aphids (

).

In plants, the biosynthesis of monoterpenes normally occurs in plastids, where GPP is synthesized, while the formation of sesquiterpenes occurs in the cytosol, where FPP is generated (

; 

). 
A
subcellular localization study confirmed LoTPS2 to be localized to the cytosol, where it specifically catalyzes the transformation of FPP into (
E
, 
E
)-α- farnesene, whereas LoTPS4 localizes to plastids. Metabolic engineering of terpene synthase genes in tobacco, 

Arabidopsis
, Fragaria species

and potato showed the existence of a small pool of GPP in the cytosol and FPP in the plastids (

; 

; 

). Likewise, 
TPS02
from 

Arabidopsis

is able to utilize both GPP and FPP to produce monoterpenes and sesquiterpenes, respectively (

). However, the presence of different amounts of substrate (high FPP/low GPP in the cytosol and vice versa in plastids) would permit dual activity of the enzyme to produce monoterpenes and sesquiterpenes in both locations. LoTPS4 probably acts mainly as a monoterpene synthase, as sesquiterpene products produced by LoTPS4 were detected in the floral volatile profile of 

Lilium

‘Siberia’ at some stages under the experimental conditions of the present study.

All chemicals and reagents were obtained from Sigma-Aldrich, Sangon Biotech, Takara (
Japan
), Magen and Thermo Fisher Scientific unless otherwise stated. Geranyl pyrophosphate (GPP), farnesyl pyrophosphate (FPP), geranylgeranyl diphosphate (GGPP) and terpenoid standards were obtained from Sigma-Aldrich.

The alignment of amino acid sequences was carried out with ClustalX 2.1 (

) and shaded with GeneDoc. For the phylogenetic tree, amino acid sequences were aligned with ClustalX 2.1, and the phylogenetic tree was constructed via the neighbor-joining method in MEGA 6 (

). The sequence data of the genes are given in the additional file.

For functional characterization of the LoTPSs, their sequences were cloned into the expression vector pET-30a (Novagen) using the Kpn 1 site as a start codon and Not 1 downstream of the stop codon as described previously (
). The ORFs were amplified by polymerase chain reaction (PCR) using high-fidelity KOD-Plus DNA polymerase (TOYOBA). Sequence analysis showed that the sequences were correctly introduced without error. Thereafter, the expression constructs were transformed into
E. coli
Rosetta-gammi B (DE3) competent cells. A verified single colony of transformants was incubated overnight at 37 ̊C at 120 rpm in Luria-Bertani (LB) medium supplemented with kanamycin (100 μg/ml) and chloramphenicol (34 μg/ml). The next day, the culture was diluted 1:50 with LB medium supplemented with antibiotics and under the same conditions as described above until an OD 600 of 0.4–0.8 was observed. The culture was incubated at 16 ̊C and 120 rpm after the induction of expression by adding isopropyl-β- D-thiogalactopyranoside (IPTG). The next day, the cells were harvested via centrifugation ( 5000 g , 10 min) followed by sonication as described previously (
). Thereafter, the lysates were subjected to purification by loading onto Ni–NTA HisPur Resins (Thermo Fisher) according to the manufacturer's instructions. All steps were carried out at 4 ̊C. The protein concentration was determined through the Bradford method using BSA as a standard.

Different computer-based prediction servers (TargetP [http://www. cbs.dtu.dk/services/TargetP/], ChloroP [http://www.cbs.dtu.dk/ services/ChloroP/], WoLF PSORT [http://wolfpsort.seq.cbrc.jp/], SignalP [http://www.cbs.dtu.dk/services/SignalP/], Predotar [http:// urgi.versailles.inra.fr/predotar], iPSORT [http://ipsort.hgc.jp/predict. cgi], and PredisSi [http://www.predisi.de/index.html] were used to analyze the N-terminal sequences of LoTPS2 and LoTPS4. The 240-bp fragments encoding the 80 aa N-terminal peptides of LoTPS2 and LoTPS4 were amplified via PCR with an Spe 1 site at the 5′ end and an Nco1 site at the 3′ end of both inserts and these sequences were cloned into the p35 S-EGFP-1 vector (
). Similarly, the full-length sequence of LoTPS2 was cloned into the p35 S-EGFP-1 vector selecting a Sal 1 site at the 5′ end and a Sac1 site at the 3′ end, while for LoTPS4, a Sac1 site was selected at the 5′ end and Nco1 site at the 3′ end. The accuracy of the insertion of the sequences into the vector was confirmed. The isolation and transformation of protoplasts from
Arabidopsis
were carried out as described by Sheen (
). Protoplasts were observed 16 h after transformation through Leica TCS SP2 AOBS Spectral Confocal Scanner and further processed by Adobe Photoshop. The primers used in the study are listed in Supplementary Table 2.
